==English==

===Etymology 1===
Late 17th century, unknown origin, possibly {{Cy.}} ''[[moedrodd]]'' to worry or bother. Possible alternatve from the {{Cy.}} '"meidda"' - to beg for whey or perhaps "meiddio" - to dare or venture. Bear in mind that the dd in Welsh corresponds in sound to the "th" in mither.

====Pronunciation====
*{{IPA|/ˈmaɪθər/}}

====Verb====
{{en-verb|mithers|mithering|mithered|mithered}}

# {{context|intransitive|North England dialect}} To make an [[unnecessary]] [[fuss]], [[moan]].
# {{transitive}} To [[pester]] or [[irritate]] someone. Usually directed at [[children]]; 
#: ''"Will you stop '''mithering''' me!"''

